The Core Systems of BepuPhysics2 form the foundation of the physics engine, providing the essential components that manage simulation entities, detect collisions, solve constraints, and integrate motion. This page offers an overview of these primary components and how they interact to create a complete physics simulation. For detailed information about specific systems, refer to their dedicated pages such as Simulation, Bodies Management, Shape System, and Pose Integration.

Architecture Overview

BepuPhysics2 is organized around several interconnected core systems, each responsible for a specific aspect of the physics simulation.

Core Systems Relationships Diagram

Sources: BepuPhysics/Simulation.cs16-70 BepuPhysics/Simulation.cs106-166

Simulation Class

The Simulation class is the central orchestrator that ties together all other systems. It manages the timestepping process and provides a high-level interface for users of the physics engine.

Simulation Class Diagram

The Simulation provides methods that encapsulate the major stages of a physics update:

  1. Sleep(): Moves candidate bodies to inactive islands
  2. PredictBoundingBoxes(): Updates bounding boxes for collision detection
  3. CollisionDetection(): Finds and processes collisions between objects
  4. Solve(): Resolves constraints and updates velocities
  5. IncrementallyOptimizeDataStructures(): Improves memory layout for better performance

Sources: BepuPhysics/Simulation.cs229-305

Physics Pipeline Flow

A complete physics update consists of several stages executed in sequence, forming the simulation pipeline.

Physics Pipeline Flow Diagram

Sources: BepuPhysics/Simulation.cs316-326

Bodies System

The Bodies class manages all dynamic entities in the simulation. It maintains collections of active and inactive bodies along with their properties.

Bodies System Diagram

Key components:

  • BodySet: Contains arrays of body properties
  • BodyReference: Provides a convenient API for accessing and modifying body properties
  • BodyHandle: Used to reference bodies through indirect lookup

Sources: BepuPhysics/Bodies.cs32-184 BepuPhysics/BodySet.cs20-121 BepuPhysics/BodyReference.cs13-209

Body Properties

Bodies have several property types that define their physical characteristics and state.

Body Properties Diagram

Sources: BepuPhysics/BodyProperties.cs12-45 BepuPhysics/BodyProperties.cs54-183 BepuPhysics/BodyProperties.cs189-252 BepuPhysics/BodyProperties.cs259-350

Solver System

The Solver handles resolving constraints between bodies. It organizes constraints into batches and type batches for efficient processing.

Solver System Diagram

Key concepts:

  • Batches: Groups of constraints that can be solved in parallel
  • Type Batches: Groups of constraints of the same type, which can be processed using the same code
  • Fallback Batch: Special batch for handling high body-constraint connectivity

Sources: BepuPhysics/Solver.cs19-178 BepuPhysics/Constraints/TypeProcessor.cs23-218

The Core Systems of BepuPhysics2 work together to provide a complete physics simulation pipeline, from collision detection to constraint solving and pose integration. Each system is designed to be highly performant while maintaining accuracy and stability in the simulation. For more details on specific systems, refer to their dedicated pages.
